  <section class="sec">
    <p class="sl">Local knowledge</p>
    <h2>Ivanhoe — Federation Bungalows, Yarra Gorge Cold, Period Chimney Systems</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Ivanhoe occupies the high ground above the Yarra River's lower gorge section, developed from the 1880s through the interwar period as one of Melbourne's most pleasant middle-class riverside suburbs. The suburb is characterised by Federation bungalows, Edwardian cottages and interwar brick homes on generous sloping blocks, many of which retain their original chimneys and fireplaces. The Yarra River gorge that borders Ivanhoe's western and southern edges creates a pronounced cold microclimate: cold air drains off the Templestowe plateau to the east and pools in the Yarra valley floor, and the river itself contributes moisture that makes Ivanhoe's winter mornings noticeably colder and damper than surrounding higher ground. The elevated streets along the Ivanhoe ridge can also be exposed to sharp north-westerly winds through June and July. Many Ivanhoe homes are well-maintained period properties with working fireplaces that owners use consistently through winter. We service Ivanhoe and the broader Heidelberg area regularly and are familiar with the period chimney systems and sloping-block configurations common throughout the suburb.</p></div>
  </section>

